2. 🎯 Problem Statement

2.1 The Safety-Generalization Dichotomy

Contemporary robotics faces a fundamental tension between semantically rich but unverifiable learning-based methods and provably safe but semantically blind classical control. This gap is particularly acute in the context of Vision-Language-Action (VLA) foundation models, which achieve remarkable generalization but offer no stability guarantees.

Paradigm Strengths Weaknesses
Classical Control (MPC, LQR, CBF) Formal safety/stability proofs No semantic understanding, poor generalization
Foundation Models (RT-2, OpenVLA) Rich semantic grounding, few-shot generalization Black-box, no certificates, computational intractability
Geometric Deep Learning (SE(3)-Transformers) Exploits symmetry, data-efficient Typically static, not integrated with control

The Gap: No existing framework simultaneously provides:

· Formal certificates (Lyapunov stability, barrier functions)
· Semantic reasoning (language grounding, task composition)
· Computational efficiency (sparse, O(N) scaling)
· Symmetry awareness (equivariance to rotations/translations)

2.2 Related Work and Our Contribution

To substantiate the "first formal proof" claim, we survey the most recent and relevant results (2024–2026):

· Contraction on time-varying graphs: LGTC (Marino et al., CDC 2024) proves contraction for multi-agent flocking with bounded topology variations, using δ-ISS and closed-form approximations to preserve contraction rate. GN-CDE (Yu et al., 2025) models topology as a control path in Neural CDEs. Neither derives joint contraction on the coupled (state, explicit adjacency ODE) via small-gain on the product space, which is our core innovation.
· Safe VLA frameworks: AEGIS (Hu et al., Dec 2025) provides the first plug-and-play CBF layer for VLA models, projecting nominal actions via a QP with 0.356 ms overhead and achieving zero violations on SafeLIBERO. AEGIS assumes bounded uncertainty but does not derive it endogenously. CDIA's Lemma 2 fills this gap by linking the uncertainty bound directly to the contraction rate of the cognitive graph.
· Equivariant dynamic graphs: Standard SE(3)-equivariant networks (e.g., NequIP 2022, VN-EGNN 2025) are static. Our Lemma 1 proves that the adjacency evolution $\dot{A}$ remains invariant under SE(3) if attention uses invariant inner products, and Theorem 3 extends this to the full pipeline under the additional condition that the task input $u_{\text{task}}$ is SE(3)-invariant.
· LSH-based sparsity: HEPT (Miao et al., 2025) and LSH-MoE (NeurIPS 2024) apply LSH to point-cloud transformers. Our complexity analysis adapts LSH to continuous graph-ODEs with closed-form inactive-edge decay, achieving $O(N\log N)$ amortized cost while maintaining stability via error bounds (Lemma 3), assuming fixed query/key projections.

Thus, CDIA is the first architecture to combine:

· State-dependent topology evolution (cytoskeletal dynamics) with a differentiable polymerization ODE,
· Rigorous proof of joint contraction of the coupled $(Z,A)$ system via a small-gain condition,
· Endogenous uncertainty bound $D(x)$ derived from contraction, enabling robust CBF safety,
· Full-pipeline SE(3)-equivariance under dynamic graph evolution (with SE(3)-invariant task input),
· Near-linear computational scaling via LSH with provable error control (under fixed projections).

