5. 🔍 Theoretical Validation & Contributions

The thesis will contain the following original mathematical results:

1. Lemma 1: Lipschitz continuity and SE(3)-invariance of the cytoskeletal evolution $\dot{A}$.
2. Theorem 1: Coupled contraction of the joint $(Z, A)$ system with explicit small-gain condition and scaling factor, under the assumption of constant metric $M_Z$.
3. Lemma 2: Derivation of a time-dependent uncertainty bound $D(t)$ from contraction properties, linking the cognitive graph's convergence to a bound on output deviation.
4. Theorem 2: Safety guarantee via robust CBF using the derived bound, positioning CDIA as an endogenous source of uncertainty quantification.
5. Theorem 3: End-to-end SE(3)-equivariance of the entire perception-action pipeline under the additional condition that $u_{\text{task}}$ is SE(3)-invariant.
6. Lemma 3: Quantification of LSH approximation error and its effect on contraction, with guidelines for maintaining stability under fixed query/key projections.
7. Complexity Analysis: Proof that $O(N \log N)$ amortized complexity suffices via LSH and closed-form inactive-edge decay, enabling scalable real-time deployment.

