Appendix A: Mathematical Preliminaries

A.1 Lie Group SE(3) and Equivariance

Definition A.1 (Special Euclidean Group). The Lie group $SE(3) = \mathbb{R}^3 \rtimes SO(3)$ consists of pairs $(\mathbf{r}, R)$ with translation $\mathbf{r} \in \mathbb{R}^3$ and rotation $R \in SO(3)$. The group action on a point $\mathbf{p} \in \mathbb{R}^3$ is $(\mathbf{r}, R) \cdot \mathbf{p} = R\mathbf{p} + \mathbf{r}$. The Lie algebra $\mathfrak{se}(3)$ is isomorphic to $\mathbb{R}^6$ with elements $(\boldsymbol{\omega}, \mathbf{v})$, where $\boldsymbol{\omega} \in \mathbb{R}^3$ is the angular velocity and $\mathbf{v} \in \mathbb{R}^3$ the linear velocity.

Definition A.2 (Equivariant Map). Let $\rho_X: SE(3) \to \mathrm{GL}(V_X)$ and $\rho_Y: SE(3) \to \mathrm{GL}(V_Y)$ be representations on vector spaces $V_X$, $V_Y$. A map $f: V_X \to V_Y$ is equivariant if for all $g \in SE(3)$ and $x \in V_X$,
f(\rho_X(g) x) = \rho_Y(g) f(x).


In the context of this thesis, we use:

· $\rho_{\text{scene}}$: representation on scene graph node features (e.g., type-0, type-1 tensors).
· $\rho_{\text{adj}}$: trivial representation (invariance) for adjacency scalars.
· $\mathrm{Ad}_g$: adjoint action on twists $\xi \in \mathfrak{se}(3)$.

A.2 Contraction Theory

Definition A.3 (Contraction). Consider a nonlinear system $\dot{x} = f(x,t)$ with $f$ smooth. The system is contracting with rate $\beta > 0$ in a metric $M(x,t) \succ 0$ if for all $x,t$ and all virtual displacements $\delta x$,
\frac{d}{dt}(\delta x^\top M \delta x) \leq -2\beta \,\delta x^\top M \delta x.


Equivalently, the generalized Jacobian
F = \dot{M} + M\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} + \frac{\partial f}{\partial x}^\top M


satisfies $F \preceq -2\beta M$.

Key Properties. Contraction implies:

· Exponential convergence of any two trajectories to each other.
· Existence of a unique steady-state trajectory for given inputs.
· Robustness to bounded perturbations (Input-to-State Stability).

A.3 Control Barrier Functions (CBF)

Definition A.4 (Control Barrier Function). Let $\mathcal{C} = \{ x \in \mathbb{R}^n \mid h(x) \geq 0 \}$ be a safe set with $\partial h/\partial x \neq 0$ on $\partial \mathcal{C}$. $h$ is a CBF for the control-affine system $\dot{x} = f(x) + g(x)u$ if there exists an extended class-$\mathcal{K}_\infty$ function $\alpha$ such that for all $x \in \mathcal{C}$,
\sup_{u \in \mathcal{U}} \left[ L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) u + \alpha(h(x)) \right] \geq 0.

Robust CBF (Taylor et al. 2020). When the dynamics are uncertain, $f = \hat{f} + \delta$ with $\|\delta(x)\| \leq D(x)$, a sufficient condition for safety is
L_{\hat{f}}h + L_g h u - \|L_\delta h\|_* D(x) + \alpha(h) \geq 0.

A.4 Graph Neural ODEs

A Graph Neural ODE (Poli et al. 2019) is a continuous-depth GNN where node features evolve according to an ODE:
\dot{Z} = \mathrm{GNN}(Z, A, \theta),


with adjacency $A$. In this thesis, both $Z$ and $A$ evolve, leading to a coupled system:
\dot{Z} = G(Z, A, u_{\text{task}}),\qquad \dot{A} = \mathcal{F}(Z, A, u_{\text{task}}).

